ankrig","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"7 January 1121–7 January 1182":"7 januari 1121–7 januari 1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","1125–Female":"1125–Overleden","1127–Female":"1127–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1120–Female":"1120–Overleden","1145–1182":"1145–1182","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1104–Female":"1104–Overleden","1127":"1127","7 January 1182":"7 januari 1182","1104":"1104","7 January 1121":"7 januari 1121","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1101":"1101","1121":"1121","1120":"1120","7 Jan 1182":"7 januari 1182","1182":"1182","Argentan, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Argentan, Orne, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Chateau-Landon, Gatinais, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"7 January 1121–7 January 1182":"7 January 1121–7 January 1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","1125–Female":"1125–Deceased","1127–Female":"1127–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","1145–1182":"1145–1182","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1104–Female":"1104–Deceased","1127":"1127","7 January 1182":"7 January 1182","1104":"1104","7 January 1121":"7 January 1121","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1101":"1101","1121":"1121","1120":"1120","7 Jan 1182":"7 January 1182","1182":"1182","Argentan, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Argentan, Orne, Lower Normandy, France","Chateau-Landon, Gatinais, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clement","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alcide, Alphonse, Andre, Marcel, Armand, Cecile, Christophe, Gaston, Olivier, Aime.","English, Catalan, German, Flemish, and Dutch; French and Walloon (<b>Clément</b>): from the Latin personal name <i>Clemens</i> meaning ‘merciful’ (genitive <i>Clementis</i>). This achieved popularity firstly through having been borne by an early Christian saint who was a disciple of Saint Paul, and later because it was selected as a symbolic name by a number of early popes. There has also been some confusion with the personal name <i>Clemence</i> (from Latin <i>Clementia</i>, meaning ‘mercy’, an abstract noun derived from the adjective; in part a masculine name from Latin <i>Clementius</i>, a later derivative of <i>Clemens</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Clemente  , and also their derivatives."],"variants":[{"name":"Clem","meanings":["English (Somerset): from a short form of the personal name   Clement   or of the female form, <i>Clemence</i>.","Americanized form of German <b>Klemm</b> and German or Dutch <b>Klem</b>: from a short form of the personal name   Klemens  ."]},{"name":"Clements","meanings":["English, Irish (Tyrone and Antrim), and Dutch: variant of   Clement  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Clementz   and Slovenian patronymic <b>Klemenc</b> (see   Klements  )."]},{"name":"Clemente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Elia, Manuel, Cesar, Fernando, Luis, Rafael, Alfredo, Andres, Armando, Gerardo.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Salvatore, Vito, Gino, Angelo, Nicola, Rocco, Enrico, Guido, Marco, Matteo.  Portuguese Joaquim.","Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese: from the personal name<i>Clemente</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Crimi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Gaetano, Vita, Cosimo, Giuseppe, Luciano, Luigi, Sal, Tommaso.","Italian (Sicily): from an altered form of the medieval Greek personal name <i>Klēmēs</i>, from Latin <i>Clemens</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Chimenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Francesco, Filomena, Guido.","Italian (southern): variant of <b>Clementi</b> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clemon","meanings":["English: probably from a variant of the personal name   Clement  .","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish and northern Irish   McClymont  ."]},{"name":"Klehm","meanings":["North German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Klement</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clementson","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Clement   + <i>-son</i>. See also   Clements   and   Clemson  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Klementsson</b> or <b>Clementsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Klement</i>,   Clement  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian <b>Clementsen</b> or <b>Klementsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Kelemen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Andras, Gabor, Geza, Imre, Laszlo, Tibor, Bela, Gyula, Istvan, Jozsef, Karoly, Leszlo.","Hungarian, Croatian, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian: from the personal name <i>Kelemen</i>, Hungarian form of   Clement  . The Hungarian surname is also common in Romania."]},{"name":"Climie","meanings":["Scottish: from a Scots pet form of the personal name   Clement  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Clement was born on 7 January 1121, in Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France, his father, Lord Robert I d'Nemours Clement Lord, was 20 and his mother, Beline DE CHATEAU LANDON, was 18. He had at least 1 son with Mahaut Du Tourneau. He died on 7 January 1182, in Argentan, Orne, Lower Normandy, France, at the age of 61."},"et":{"7 January 1121–7 January 1182":"7. jaanuar 1121–7. jaanuar 1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1145–1182":"1145–1182","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1127":"1127"